data.notes: Available during accumulation phase. Upon death of the owner, benefit will be equal to contract value. There is an Extended Legacy Program, offered by issuer, for beneficiaries to continue the contract after the death of the owner. The program is not available under rollover contracts and with any other than 5-year settlement option. Upon election, beneficiary may choose to receive the death benefit under either 1) a 5-year settlement option (starting from death of owner); or 2) in the form of withdrawals for a longer period of time. Issuer will charge the beneficiary an annual base contract expense of 1.15%. This charge is deducted daily from the average daily ending net asset value allocated to the Variable Portfolios.

data.notes: Available during the accumulation phase. Upon the death of an owner (without living benefit), the benefit will be greatest of -1) contract value, 2) net purchase payments; increased by subsequent purchase payments, adjusted for withdrawals (includes advisory fees; if applicable) or 3) highest contract value on any contract anniversary prior to owner's 83rd birthday or death. Upon death of owner (with living benefit), benefit will be greatest of -1) contract value, 2) purchase payments reduced by - a) any withdrawal adjustments if living benefit is not terminated, or b) any withdrawals prior to the date living benefit is terminated, or 3) highest contract value on any contract anniversary prior to owner's 83rd birthday or death reduced by - a) any Withdrawal Adjustments since contract anniversary if living benefit is not terminated, b) any withdrawal adjustments since contract anniversary, prior to the date the Living Benefit is terminated and reduced for a withdrawals in the same proportion that the withdrawal reduced the contract value on the date of such withdrawal on or after the date the living benefit is terminated and The Maximum Anniversary Value death benefit can only be elected prior to your 81st birthday.

data.name: Polaris Income Plus
data.availPrescribedAssetLocation: Owner must participate in Asset Allocation Program.
data.availRestrictionFxdAccount: Owner must allocate 10% of each purchase payment and spousal continuation contribution to the secure value account.
data.availWhenAdded: No longer available for new purchases.
data.change: Once elected may not be changed.
data.effectChangeOwnership: Change in ownership will result in termination of rider except under certain conditions.
data.gmwbCancellation: May be cancelled on 5th anniversary or any rider anniversary thereafter.
data.spousalContinuationOption: Surviving spouse may elect to continue benefit after death of owner under joint life option.
data.subsequentPremium: Subsequent Eligible Purchase Payments through the 1st contract year increase the Benefit Base and Income Credit Base by dollar for dollar. The MAW and Protected Income Payment amounts are increased by the appropriate % multiplied by the amount of the subsequent Eligible Purchase Payment.
data.partialWithdrawals: When withdrawals in a rider year exceed the maximum annual withdrawal amount, the Income Base and Income Credit Base are reduced in the same proportion that the contract value is reduced for the excess withdrawal. The maximum annual withdrawal amount is reset to the maximum annual withdrawal % multiplied by the new Benefit Base.
data.reqdMinDistributions: RMD withdrawals in excess of the maximum annual withdrawal amount are not considered to be excess withdrawals.
data.benefitDescription: The rider provides a guaranteed lifetime income plus the opportunity to increase income by locking in the greater of either the contract's highest anniversary value, or an annual Income Credit.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Living Benefit locks in the greater of two values to determine the Income Base. The Income Base is the basis for the Covered Persons' guaranteed lifetime benefit which must be taken in a series of withdrawals. Income Base is initially equal to the first Eligible Purchase Payment, thereafter, automatically locked in on each Benefit Year Anniversary, to the greater of - 1) highest Anniversary Value; or 2) current Income Base increased by any available Income Credit.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: Issuer may increase benefit base by 6%, until 12th rider anniversary, if no withdrawals has been taken during benefit year. Income Base will be set equal to greater of - 1) income base based on maximum anniversary value, or 2) income base plus income credit. If no withdrawal is taken, the Minimum Income Base on the 12th Benefit Year anniversary is the greater of - a) current Income Base, or b) Minimum Income Base. Income Credit percentage on the rider anniversary is reduced but not eliminated in any rider year in which cumulative withdrawals are less than 6% of the Income Base and not greater than the maximum annual withdrawal amount.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: On the 12th contract anniversary, the income base will be increased to at least 200% of the purchase payments where eligible purchase payments are 100% of the purchase payments made in the first contract year and are included in the calculation of the income credit base, provided no withdrawals are taken prior to that anniversary.
data.notes: If the contract value is reduced to zero but Income Base is greater than zero, Issuer will pay the remaining Maximum Annual Withdrawal Amount. Thereafter Issuer will pay the Protected Income Payment over the remaining lifetime of the annuitant. Effective January 15, 2016, if owner elect this rider, and contract issue date is on January 23, 2012 or later, Issuer will not accept subsequent purchase payments after 12 months (60 months if contract issued date prior to January 23, 2012) from contract issue date.
data.otherInfo: Effective from May 1, 2014, rider name changed from SunAmerica Income Plus to Polaris Income Plus.
data.withdrawalNotes: Income percentages displayed above for Income Options 1&2 are available while the account value is greater than $0. If the account value is reduced to 0 and the 1st withdrawal was taken at age 65 or later, the client will receive the Protected Income Payment of 4% for Income Option 1 or 3% for Income option 2. If the 1st withdrawal was taken prior to age 65, Protected Income Payments for both Income Options 1 & 2 will be 3%. This rate will increase to 4% if the income base is increased due to an account value step-up at age 65 or later while there is account value in the contract.
data.chargeNotes: Rider fee is calculated as a percentage of Income Base and is deducted on quarterly anniversaries. The quarterly fee rate will not decrease or increase by more than 0.10% each quarter. Charge will be deducted pro-rata from Variable Portfolios for OR, TX and WA.
data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate 10% in Secure Value Account and remaining 90% must be in the specified sub-accounts and DCA fixed account under group A & B, where 50% of this 90% allocation must be made under the Var Invt options specified under group B.

data.gmwbCancellation: May be cancelled on 5th anniversary or any rider anniversary thereafter.
data.gmwbTermination: Benefit will automatically terminate upon earliest of - 1) annuitization, 2) surrender, 3) death, or 4) benefit base reduces to zero.
data.spousalContinuationOption: Surviving spouse may elect to continue benefit after death of owner under joint life option.
data.subsequentPremium: Subsequent Eligible Purchase Payments through the 1st contract year increase the Benefit Base and Income Credit Base by dollar for dollar. The MAW and Protected Income Payment amounts are increased by the appropriate % multiplied by the amount of the subsequent Eligible Purchase Payment.
data.partialWithdrawals: When withdrawals in a rider year exceed the MAW amount, the Income Base and Income Credit Base are reduced in the same proportion that the contract value is reduced for the excess withdrawal. The MAW amount is reset to the MAW % multiplied by the new Benefit Base.
data.reqdMinDistributions: RMD withdrawals in excess of the MAW amount are not considered to be excess withdrawals.
data.benefitDescription: The rider provides a guaranteed lifetime income.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Living Benefit lock in the greater of two values to determine the Income Base. The Income Base is the basis for the Covered Persons' guaranteed lifetime benefit which must be taken in a series of withdrawals. Income Base is initially equal to the first Eligible Purchase Payment, thereafter, automatically locked in on each Benefit Year Anniversary, to the greater of (1) the highest Anniversary Value, or (2) the current Income Base increased by any available Income Credit.
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: Issuer may increase benefit base by 5%, until 12th rider anniversary, if withdrawals taken during benefit year are less than or equal to annual benefit payments. Income Base will be set equal to greater of - 1) income base based on maximum anniversary value, or 2) income base plus income credit. If no withdrawal is taken, the Minimum Income Base on the 12th Benefit Year anniversary is the greater of - a) current Income Base, or b) Minimum Income Base.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: On the 12th contract anniversary, the Income Base will be increased to at least 200% of the Purchase Payments where Eligible Purchase Payments are 100% of the Purchase Payments made in the first contract year and are included in the calculation of the Income Credit Base, provided no withdrawals are taken prior to that anniversary.
data.notes: 100% of purchase payments made during first contract year are taken into consideration in determining the Eligible Purchase Payments. Effective January 15, 2016, if owner elect this rider, and contract issue date is on January 23, 2012 or later, Issuer will not accept subsequent purchase payments after 12 months (60 months if contract issued date prior to January 23, 2012) from contract issue date. Maximum annual withdrawal amount which represents maximum amount that may be withdrawn each benefit year while contract value is greater than zero, without reducing income base, and if applicable, income credit base. The maximum annual withdrawal amount is calculated by multiplying income base by applicable maximum annual withdrawal percentage. If contract value is reduced to zero but income base is greater than zero, the protected income payment is determined by multiplying income base by the applicable protected income payment percentage. For Protected Income Payment, Annual Withdrawal Percentage is 5.4% for single life and 4.9% for joint life for age 65 and older.
data.otherInfo: Effective from May 1, 2014, rider name changed from SunAmerica Income Builder to Polaris Income Builder.
data.chargeNotes: Rider fees is calculated as a percentage of the Income Base and is deducted on quarterly anniversaries of the rider effective date and begin on the date the rider takes effect. The quarterly fee rate will not decrease or increase by more than 0.10% each quarter.
data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate 10% in Secure Value Account and up to 90% must be distributed in specified sub-accounts Group A. Up to 50% of amount invested in Group A must be allocated in sub-account Group B.

data.name: Polaris Income Max
data.availPrescribedAssetLocation: Owner must select an Asset Allocation Program.
data.availRestrictionFxdAccount: 20% of the total contribution made into the contract must be allocated to the Secure Value Account, regardless of 80% of allocation made to the issuer designed asset allocation portfolio.
data.change: There is a one-time opportunity to change the Income Option on the activation date for an additional annual fee of 0.25%.
data.effectChangeOwnership: Change in ownership will result in termination of rider except under certain conditions.
data.gmwbTermination: Benefit will automatically terminate upon earliest of - 1) annuitization, 2) surrender, 3) death, or 4) benefit base reduces to zero.
data.spousalContinuationOption: A surviving spouse may elect to continue benefit after the death of owner.
data.subsequentPremium: Subsequent Purchase Payments are not allowed after owner's and/or annuitant's attained age 80 with optional living benefit. Subsequent Eligible Purchase Payments increase the benefit base dollar for dollar and the MAW amount by the MAW % multiplied by the amount of the subsequent purchase payment.
data.partialWithdrawals: When withdrawals in a rider year exceed the maximum annual withdrawal amount, the Income Base and Income Credit Base are reduced in the same proportion that the contract value is reduced for the excess withdrawal. The maximum annual withdrawal amount is reset to the maximum annual withdrawal % multiplied by the new Benefit Base.
data.reqdMinDistributions: RMD withdrawals in excess of the MAW amount are not considered to be excess withdrawals.
data.benefitDescription: Rider provides lifetime guaranteed lifetime income plus the opportunity to increase income by locking in the greater of either the contracts Higher Anniversary Value, or an Income Base with an annual Income Credit. Owner have 3 different Income Options to choose from and rider offers flexibility to make one-time change to owner's initial elections of 1) covered person and 2) income option on the Activation Date.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Income Base is determined by the Higher Anniversary Value on annual basis. Initially the Income Base is equal to the initial purchase payment, thereafter is increased by each subsequent Purchase Payment received, and is reduced proportionally by any withdrawals taken prior to the Activation Date and Excess Withdrawals taken on or after the Activation Date. Income base on each Benefit Year Anniversary, automatically locked in to the greater of - 1) highest Anniversary Value, or 2) Income Base increased by any available Income Credit. Additionally, issuer provides Income Credit of 7.0% on every benefit year anniversary , prior to the activation date. Income Base is used to determine the Maximum Withdrawal Amount that can be withdrawn under the rider. Maximum amount withdrawn on or after the activation date, while contract value is greater than zero, is equal to the Maximum Annual Withdrawal Percentage multiplied by the Income Base. Protected Income Payment, if contract value reduces to zero, but Income Base is greater than zero after the Activation Date, is equal to the Protected Income Payment Percentage multiplied by the Income Base.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: Prior to the Activation Date, the Income Base is automatically increased to the greater of (1) the Higher Anniversary Value; or (2) the current Income Base plus the Income Credit. If the Income Base is increased to a Higher Anniversary Value, the Income Credit Base is also automatically increased to that Higher Anniversary Value. The Income Credit Base is not increased if an Income Credit is added to the Income Base.
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: Income Base is used to determine the Maximum Withdrawal Amount that can be withdrawn under the rider. Maximum amount withdrawn on or after the activation date, while contract value is greater than zero, is equal to the Maximum Annual Withdrawal Percentage multiplied by the Income Base. Maximum amount withdrawn if contract value reduces to zero, but Income Base is greater than zero after the Activation Date, is equal to the Protected Income Payment Percentage multiplied by the Income Base.
data.notes: Owner can change the Income Option on the Activation Date (quarterly fee rate can increase no more than 0.1625%) the Lifetime Income Option Change Fee will be assessed and deducted from your contract value starting on the first Benefit Quarter Anniversary following the Activation Date and quarterly thereafter.
data.withdrawalNotes: Protected Income Payment Percentage will be 4.25% for single life & 4.0% for joint life for option I, if the Income Base is increased to a new Highest Anniversary Value on or after the covered person's (65th birthday).
data.chargeNotes: Rider fees are deducted on quarterly anniversaries of the rider effective date and begin on the date the rider takes effect.
data.feeOption: The fee rate can increase or decrease no more than 0.10% each quarter (0.40%/4). The change in fee percentage is determined by the change in Volatility Index (VIX) decreases or increases, the fee rate will decrease or increase accordingly.
data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate 20% in Secure Value Account and remaining 80% must be in the Variable Portfolios.

data.availPrescribedAssetLocation: Owner must select an Asset Allocation Program.

data.change: There is a one-time opportunity to change the Income Option on the activation date for an additional annual fee of 0.25%.
data.effectChangeOwnership: Change in ownership will result in termination of rider except, change is due to marriage, divorce, or death prior to the activation date. However, at least one of the original named Covered Person(s) must remain in the contract.
data.spousalContinuationOption: Surviving spouse may elect to continue benefit after death of owner under joint life option.
data.subsequentPremium: Subsequent Purchase Payments are not allowed after owner's and/or annuitant's attained age 80 with optional living benefit. Subsequent Eligible Purchase Payments increase the benefit base dollar for dollar and the MAW amount by the MAW % multiplied by the amount of the subsequent purchase payment.
data.partialWithdrawals: Withdrawal reduces the Income Base, Minimum Income Base and Step-up Values proportionally to the reduction in the contract value.
data.reqdMinDistributions: RMD withdrawals in excess of the MAW amount are not considered to be excess withdrawals.
data.benefitDescription: Rider provides lifetime guaranteed income stream plus the opportunity to increase income by locking in step-up values. Owner have 3 different Income Options to choose from and rider offers flexibility to make one-time change to owner's initial elections of 1) covered person and 2) income option on the Activation Date.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Income Base is determined by the Step-up Values on daily basis. Initially the Income Base is equal to the initial purchase payment, thereafter is increased by each subsequent Purchase Payment received, and is reduced proportionally by any withdrawals taken prior to the Activation Date and Excess Withdrawals taken on or after the Activation Date. Additionally, issuer provides Minimum Income Base on every benefit year anniversary and Daily Step-up Values, prior to the activation date. Income Base is used to determine the Maximum Withdrawal Amount that can be withdrawn under the rider. Maximum amount withdrawn on or after the activation date, while contract value is greater than zero, is equal to the Maximum Annual Withdrawal Percentage multiplied by the Income Base. Maximum amount withdrawn if contract value reduces to zero, but Income Base is greater than zero after the Activation Date, is equal to the Protected Income Payment Percentage multiplied by the Income Base.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: Prior to the Activation Date, the Income Base is increased daily to the Step-up values and by subsequent purchase payments, if any. Additionally, Income Base is increased to at least the Minimum Income Base on the Benefit Year Anniversary compounding at 6% annually.
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: On or after the Activation Date, Income Base is increased only on the Benefit Year Anniversary by looking back to the Higher Step-up Value since the Activation Date.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: The Step-up value is used to determine the Income Base and is initially equals to the contract value. Then on any day, prior to the activation date, if Contract Value is greater than the Income Base, the Income Base is stepped up to that Contract Value.
data.notes: Owner can change the Income Option on the Activation Date (quarterly fee rate can increase no more than 0.1625%) the Lifetime Income Option Change Fee will be assessed and deducted from your contract value starting on the first Benefit Quarter Anniversary following the Activation Date and quarterly thereafter.
data.withdrawalNotes: Protected Income Payment Percentage will be 4.25% for single life & 4.0% for joint life for option I, if the Income Base is increased to a new Highest Anniversary Value on or after the covered person's (65th birthday).
data.chargeNotes: Rider fee is calculated as a percentage of the Income Base and is deducted on quarterly anniversaries of the rider effective date and begin on the date the rider takes effect. The quarterly fee rate will not decrease or increase by more than 0.10% each quarter.
data.initialResetText: If one or more Excess Withdrawals have been taken in that Benefit Year, the Income Base is increased on the Benefit Year Anniversary by looking back to the highest Step-up Value since the last Excess Withdrawal.
data.feeOption: The fee rate can increase or decrease no more than 0.10% each quarter (0.40%/4). The change in fee percentage is determined by the change in Volatility Index (VIX) decreases or increases, the fee rate will decrease or increase accordingly.
data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate 10% in Secure Value Account and the remaining 90% must be distributed as following Variable Portfolios in 1)Asset Allocation Portfolios or else by choosing 2) Build your own allocation.

vaCharges.yearCalculatedOn: Issuer imposes CDSC on each purchase payment based on number of completed years since received.
vaCharges.waiverNotes: Nursing Home Waiver Is Not Available in CA, MO, CT, MA and PA.

vaWithdrawals.notes: For withdrawals of $500,000 and more, Owner is required to include signature guarantee issued by broker-dealer which verifies the validity of signature. In Texas, the min remaining contract value is $2000.

data.notes: In Texas, the min remaining contract value is $2000.

vaSchdTransAssetRebalancings.notes: If optional living benefit is elected, Automatic Asset Rebalancing Program will automatically be enrolled with quarterly rebalancing. Secure Value Account not available with the rebalancing program.
vaSchdTransAssetRebalancings.assetRebalCancellation: May be cancelled any time after election.
vaSchdTransAssetRebalancings.assetRebalTermination: May be cancelled any time after election.

vaSchdTransDollarCostAverages.notes: The DCA Program allows to invest gradually in available investment options at no additional cost.
vaSchdTransDollarCostAverages.dcaCancellation: May be cancelled any time after election.
vaSchdTransDollarCostAverages.dcaTermination: May be terminated any time after election.

vaSchdTransDollarCostAverages.notes: The owner must allocate at least $600 for 6-month DCA Fixed Account, $1,200 for 12-month DCA Fixed Account. Availability may be restricted based on date of contract issuance and election of optional benefits.

data.otherAnnuityOption: Polaris Income Plus and Polaris Income Plus Daily.
